  "text": "Stack clash protection in GCC is implemented across multiple files. The core generic expansion is in gcc/explow.cc, which contains anti_adjust_stack_and_probe_stack_clash() (line 2072), the main generic implementation that probes stack space during allocation to prevent stack-clash attacks. This function is designed to never skip probes and safely handles residual allocations. The generic anti_adjust_stack_and_probe() function (line 2201) provides standard stack probing. Helper functions compute_stack_clash_protection_loop_data() (line 1955) and the emit_stack_clash_protection_probe_loop_* functions (lines 2014, 2036) support the main implementation.\n\nFor x86_64 targets, gcc/config/i386/i386.cc contains the architecture-specific implementation. The key function is ix86_adjust_stack_and_probe() (line 8215), which implements the prologue stack clash protection for the x86_64 architecture. It handles both inline probing for small allocations and loop-based probing for larger allocations. The get_probe_interval() function (line 6935) determines the probe interval based on the flag_stack_clash_protection flag and the param_stack_clash_protection_probe_interval parameter.\n\nThe command-line interface is defined in gcc/common.opt (line 3054-3057), where fstack-clash-protection is declared as a common optimization flag with the variable flag_stack_clash_protection.\n\nThe target infrastructure hook TARGET_STACK_CLASH_PROTECTION_ALLOCA_PROBE_RANGE is declared in gcc/target.def (line 6535) and has a default implementation in gcc/targhooks.h and gcc/targhooks.cc as default_stack_clash_protection_alloca_probe_range().\n\nThe implementation is tested in gcc/testsuite/gcc.target/i386/stack-clash-protection.c, which validates that the -fstack-clash-protection flag properly generates code for stack clash mitigation on x86_64 systems."
}

